    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1984-04-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1984-04-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="162"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d162">
                <head>162. Paper Prepared in the Department of State<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d162fn1">Source: Department of State, Bureau of Economic Affairs,
                        Office of Economical and Agricultural Affairs Files, Official Economic
                        Summit Files, 1975–1991, Lot 93D490: London Summit—Deaver—Clark 1984.
                        Confidential. Sent under an April 9 covering memorandum from <persName
                            corresp="#p_WWA_1">Wallis</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_MFRCB_1"
                            >McFarlane</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_DMK_1"
                        >Deaver</persName>. Copies were sent to <persName corresp="#p_SBW_1"
                            >Sprinkel</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MMDW_1">McMinn</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_SMB_1">Smith</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_MMMA_1">McManus</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-editorial-annotation"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1984-04-09">undated</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">REPORT OF SECOND PREPARATORY SESSION FOR LONDON ECONOMIC SUMMIT</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion not focused on international debt issues.]</p>
                <p>The discussion of the international debt situation was the other important theme
                    and went well. The basic strategy on debt outlined at Williamsburg was
                        confirmed.<note n="2" xml:id="d162fn2">See <ref target="#d131fn4">footnote
                            4, Document 131</ref> and <ref target="#d141fn3">footnote 3, Document
                            141</ref>.</note> In addition, there was general agreement to urge
                    Finance Ministers, international institutions and the debtor countries
                    themselves to seek and develop arrangements which could foster renewed economic
                    progress by debtor countries. These included: <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>encouragement of private direct investment;</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>closer cooperation and compatibility between the <gloss
                                target="#t_IMF_1">IMF</gloss> (focusing on shorter-term financial
                            and economic adjustment) and the World Bank (focusing on structural and
                            longer-term development needs); and</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>the probability that the World Bank could be a catalyst for long-term
                            capital investment. All delegations emphasized the importance of
                            continued world economic recovery and further trade liberalization to
                            the successful resolution of debt problems. The importance of reduced
                            interest rates was also highlighted by most of the other Summit
                            representatives.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion not focused on international debt issues.]</p>
            </div>
